divergence

operates on vector field producing a scalar field giving quantity of the gector field’s source at each points.

represents the volume density of the outward flux of a vector field from an infinitesimal volume around a given point.

definition

the divergence of a vector field F ( x ) \mathbf{F}(\mathbf{x}) F ( x ) at point x 0 x_{0} x 0 ​ is defined as the limit of the ratio of the surface integral of F \mathbf{F} F out of the closed surface of a volume V V V enclosing x 0 x_0 x 0 ​ to the volume of V V V , as V V V shrinks to zero

div ⁡ F ∣ x 0 = lim ⁡ V → 0 1 ∣ V ∣ ∯ S ( V ) F ⋅ n ^ d S \operatorname{div} \mathbf{F} \big|_{\mathbf{x}_0} = \lim_{V \to 0} \frac{1}{|V|} \oiint_{S(V)} \mathbf{F} \cdot \hat{\mathbf{n}} \, dS div F ​ x 0 ​ ​ = V → 0 lim ​ ∣ V ∣ 1 ​ ∬ ​ S ( V ) ​ F ⋅ n ^ d S

where ∣ V ∣ |V| ∣ V ∣ is the volume of V V V , S ( V ) S(V) S ( V ) is the boundary of V V V and n ^ \hat{\mathbf{n}} n ^ is the outward unit normal to that surface.

Cartesian coordinates

for a continuously differentiable vector field F = F x i + F y j + F z k \mathbf{F} = F_x \mathbf{i} + F_y \mathbf{j} + F_z \mathbf{k} F = F x ​ i + F y ​ j + F z ​ k , divergence is defined as the scalar-valued function:

div ⁡ F = ∇ ⋅ F = ( ∂ ∂ x , ∂ ∂ y , ∂ ∂ z ) ⋅ ( F x , F y , F z ) = ∂ F x ∂ x + ∂ F y ∂ y + ∂ F z ∂ z \begin{aligned} \operatorname{div} \mathbf{F} = \nabla \cdot \mathbf{F} &= \left( \frac{\partial}{\partial{x}}, \frac{\partial}{\partial{y}}, \frac{\partial}{\partial{z}} \right) \cdot \left( F_x, F_y, F_z \right) \\ &=\frac{\partial{F_x}}{\partial{x}} + \frac{\partial{F_y}}{\partial{y}} + \frac{\partial{F_z}}{\partial{z}} \end{aligned} div F = ∇ ⋅ F ​ = ( ∂ x ∂ ​ , ∂ y ∂ ​ , ∂ z ∂ ​ ) ⋅ ( F x ​ , F y ​ , F z ​ ) = ∂ x ∂ F x ​ ​ + ∂ y ∂ F y ​ ​ + ∂ z ∂ F z ​ ​ ​

Jacobian matrix

Suppose a function f : R n → R m \mathbf{f}: \mathbf{R}^n \to \mathbf{R}^m f : R n → R m is a function such that each of its first-order partial derivatives exists on R n \mathbf{R}^n R n , then the Jacobian matrix of f \mathbf{f} f is defined as follows:

J f = [ ∂ f ∂ x 1 ⋯ ∂ f ∂ x n ] = [ ∇ T f 1 ⋮ ∇ T f m ] = [ ∂ f 1 ∂ x 1 ⋯ ∂ f 1 ∂ x n ⋮ ⋱ ⋮ ∂ f m ∂ x 1 ⋯ ∂ f m ∂ x n ] . \begin{equation} \begin{aligned} \mathbf{J}_{\mathbf{f}} &= \begin{bmatrix} \frac{\partial \mathbf{f}}{\partial x_1} & \cdots & \frac{\partial \mathbf{f}}{\partial x_n} \end{bmatrix} \\ &= \begin{bmatrix} \nabla^T f_1 \\ \vdots \\ \nabla^T f_m \end{bmatrix} \\ &= \begin{bmatrix} \frac{\partial f_1}{\partial x_1} & \cdots & \frac{\partial f_1}{\partial x_n} \\ \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\ \frac{\partial f_m}{\partial x_1} & \cdots & \frac{\partial f_m}{\partial x_n} \end{bmatrix}. \end{aligned} \end{equation} J f ​ ​ = [ ∂ x 1 ​ ∂ f ​ ​ ⋯ ​ ∂ x n ​ ∂ f ​ ​ ] = ​ ∇ T f 1 ​ ⋮ ∇ T f m ​ ​ ​ = ​ ∂ x 1 ​ ∂ f 1 ​ ​ ⋮ ∂ x 1 ​ ∂ f m ​ ​ ​ ⋯ ⋱ ⋯ ​ ∂ x n ​ ∂ f 1 ​ ​ ⋮ ∂ x n ​ ∂ f m ​ ​ ​ ​ . ​ ​ ​

Jacobian determinant

When m = n m = n m = n , the Jacobian matrix is a square, so its determinant is a well-defined function of x x x 1

When m = 1 m=1 m = 1 , or f : R n → R f: \mathbf{R}^n \to \mathbf{R} f : R n → R is a scalar-valued function, then Jacobian matrix reduced to the row vector ∇ T f \nabla^T f ∇ T f , and this row vector of all first-order partial derivatives of f f f is the transpose of the gradient of f f f , or J f = ∇ T f \mathbf{J}_f = \nabla^T f J f ​ = ∇ T f

gradient

a vector field ∇ f \nabla f ∇ f whose value at a point p p p gives the direction and the rate of fastest increase.

In coordinate-free term, the gradient of a function f ( r ) f(\mathbf{r}) f ( r ) maybe defined by:

d f = ∇ f ⋅ d r df = \nabla f \cdot d \mathbf{r} df = ∇ f ⋅ d r

where d f df df is the infinitesimal change in f f f for an infinitesimal displacement d r d \mathbf{r} d r , and is seen to be maximal when d r d \mathbf{r} d r is in the direction of the gradient ∇ f \nabla f ∇ f

definition

the gradient of f f f ( ∇ f \nabla f ∇ f ) is defined as the unique vector field whose dot product with any vector v \mathbf{v} v at each point x x x is the directional derivative of f f f along v \mathbf{v} v , such that: 2

( ∇ f ( x ) ) ⋅ v = D v f ( x ) (\nabla f(x)) \cdot \mathbf{v} = D_v f(x) ( ∇ f ( x )) ⋅ v = D v ​ f ( x )
